# Budget Alert Agent — Cursor Rules

## Project overview
AI-powered personal budget tracking agent built with Python + Claude (via OpenRouter).
Monitors spending, categorizes transactions, and fires smart alerts.

## Tech stack
- Python 3.11+
- OpenRouter API (Claude claude-3-haiku model)
- SQLite for local storage
- Streamlit for UI
- pandas for data processing
- APScheduler for daily jobs
- Click for CLI

## Code style
- Type hints on every function
- Dataclasses for structured data, not raw dicts
- All API calls wrapped in try/except with meaningful errors
- Never hardcode credentials — always os.environ.get()
- Keep functions small — one job per function
- Constants in UPPER_CASE at top of file

## File responsibilities
- ingester.py     → CSV parsing + SQLite writes only
- categorizer.py  → Claude API calls for labelling only
- budget_checker.py → Pure logic, no AI calls, fully testable
- advisor.py      → Claude generates human-readable messages only
- alert_engine.py → Side effects only (email/SMS/Slack)
- main.py         → CLI wiring only, no business logic
- app.py          → Streamlit UI only, imports from agent/

## AI prompt rules
- Always request JSON-only responses from Claude
- Strip markdown code fences before json.loads()
- Batch transactions — never call Claude per transaction
- Keep prompts under 2000 tokens

## Testing approach
- Mock all Claude/OpenRouter API calls in tests
- budget_checker.py must be 100% unit testable (pure functions)
- Use tests/sample_transactions.csv for integration tests

## Do not
- Call Claude more than once per batch of transactions
- Store raw API responses to disk
- Use print() in UI code — use st.write() or logging
- Commit .env, venv/, or data/transactions.db to git